# Step 3: Identify Application Communications
# Aggregate data by source and destination IP, service, and protocol
app_communication_summary = dataset.groupby(['src_ip', 'dst_ip', 'service', 'proto']).agg({
    'pktTotalCount': 'sum',
    'octetTotalCount': 'sum'
}).reset_index()

# Filter out low-volume communications
threshold = 1000  # Set a higher threshold based on your dataset
significant_communications = app_communication_summary[app_communication_summary['pktTotalCount'] > threshold]

#Step 4: Apply the Louvain Method for Community Detection
import networkx as nx
import community as community_louvain  # pip install python-louvain

# Create a NetworkX graph from the significant communications
G = nx.DiGraph()

for _, row in significant_communications.iterrows():
    G.add_edge(row['src_ip'], row['dst_ip'], weight=row['pktTotalCount'], service=row['service'], protocol=row['proto'])

# Apply the Louvain method to detect communities
partition = community_louvain.best_partition(G.to_undirected())

# Add community information to nodes
for node, community in partition.items():
    G.nodes[node]['community'] = community

#Step 5: Visualize the Network with Subgraphs
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.colors as mcolors

# Function to draw subgraph for a community
def draw_community_subgraph(G, community_nodes, community_id, pos):
    subgraph = G.subgraph(community_nodes)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(subgraph, pos, node_size=3000, node_color='skyblue', edgecolors='black')
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(subgraph, pos, width=2, arrowstyle='-|>', arrowsize=20, edge_color='gray')
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(subgraph, pos, font_size=10, font_weight='bold')
    edge_labels = {(u, v): f"{d['service']}, {d['protocol']}, {d['weight']} pkt" for u, v, d in subgraph.edges(data=True)}
    nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(subgraph, pos, edge_labels=edge_labels, font_color='red', font_size=8, rotate=False)
    plt.title(f'Community {community_id} Communication', fontsize=16)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

# Get the unique communities
communities = set(partition.values())

# Define the layout for the entire graph
pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=0.5)

# Draw each community subgraph
for community in communities:
    community_nodes = [node for node, comm in partition.items() if comm == community]
    draw_community_subgraph(G, community_nodes, community, pos)

# Draw unique communication to other systems
unique_edges = [(u, v) for u, v in G.edges() if partition[u] != partition[v]]
unique_subgraph = G.edge_subgraph(unique_edges).copy()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, node_size=3000, node_color='lightgreen', edgecolors='black')
nx.draw_networkx_edges(unique_subgraph, pos, width=2, arrowstyle='-|>', arrowsize=20, edge_color='black')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, font_size=10, font_weight='bold')
unique_edge_labels = {(u, v): f"{d['service']}, {d['protocol']}, {d['weight']} pkt" for u, v, d in unique_subgraph.edges(data=True)}
nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(unique_subgraph, pos, edge_labels=unique_edge_labels, font_color='blue', font_size=8, rotate=False)
plt.title('Unique Communication to Other Systems', fontsize=16)
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

#Step 6: Visualize the Network Function to draw subgraph for a community with improved layout and alignment
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import networkx as nx
def draw_community_subgraph(G, community_nodes, community_id):
    subgraph = G.subgraph(community_nodes)
    
    # Generate positions only for the nodes in the subgraph
    pos = nx.spring_layout(subgraph, k=0.3, iterations=50)    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(subgraph, pos, node_size=2000, node_color='skyblue', edgecolors='black')
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(subgraph, pos, width=2, arrowstyle='-|>', arrowsize=15, edge_color='gray')
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(subgraph, pos, font_size=12, font_weight='bold')
    
    # Handle missing edge attributes with defaults
    edge_labels = {}
    for u, v, d in subgraph.edges(data=True):
        service = d.get('service', 'Unknown Service')
        proto = d.get('proto', 'Unknown Protocol')
        weight = d.get('weight', 0)
        edge_labels[(u, v)] = f"{service}, {proto}, {weight} pkt"    
    nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(subgraph, pos, edge_labels=edge_labels, font_color='red', font_size=8, rotate=False)    
    plt.title(f'Community {community_id} Communication', fontsize=16)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

# Get the unique communities
communities = set(partition.values())

# Draw each community subgraph with improved layout
for community in communities:
    community_nodes = [node for node, comm in partition.items() if comm == community]
    draw_community_subgraph(G, community_nodes, community)

# Draw unique communication to other systems with improved layout

unique_subgraph = G.edge_subgraph(unique_edges).copy()

# Generate positions only for the nodes in the unique communication subgraph
pos = nx.spring_layout(unique_subgraph, k=0.3, iterations=50)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(unique_subgraph, pos, node_size=2000, node_color='lightgreen', edgecolors='black')
nx.draw_networkx_edges(unique_subgraph, pos, width=2, arrowstyle='-|>', arrowsize=15, edge_color='black')

#Step 7 # Function to draw the unique communication subgraph with improved clarity
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import networkx as nx

# Function to draw the unique communication subgraph with improved clarity
def draw_unique_communication_subgraph(G, unique_edges):
    unique_subgraph = G.edge_subgraph(unique_edges).copy()
    
    # Use a different layout for better clarity
    pos = nx.kamada_kawai_layout(unique_subgraph)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(unique_subgraph, pos, node_size=2500, node_color='lightgreen', edgecolors='black')
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(unique_subgraph, pos, width=3, arrowstyle='-|>', arrowsize=15, edge_color='black')
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(unique_subgraph, pos, font_size=12, font_weight='bold', verticalalignment='center')
    
    # Adjust edge label positioning and ensure it does not overlap with nodes
    unique_edge_labels = {}
    for u, v, d in unique_subgraph.edges(data=True):
        service = d.get('service', 'Unknown Service')
        proto = d.get('proto', 'Unknown Protocol')
        weight = d.get('weight', 0)
        unique_edge_labels[(u, v)] = f"{service}, {proto}, {weight} pkt"
    
    nx.draw_networkx_edge_labels(unique_subgraph, pos, edge_labels=unique_edge_labels, font_color='blue', font_size=10, rotate=False)
    
    plt.title('Unique Communication to Other Systems', fontsize=18)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

# Identify unique communication edges between different communities
unique_edges = [(u, v) for u, v in G.edges() if partition[u] != partition[v]]

# Draw the unique communication subgraph
draw_unique_communication_subgraph(G, unique_edges)

#step8 identifiy the unknown protocols
unknown_ports = set()

for u, v, d in G.edges(data=True):
    if d.get('proto') == 'Unknown Protocol':
        unknown_ports.add(d.get('port'))


import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def lookup_protocol(port):
    url = f"https://www.speedguide.net/port.php?port={port}"
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')
    
    # Look for the protocol name on the page
    protocol = soup.find('span', {'class': 'port-name'})
    if protocol:
        return protocol.text.strip()
    else:
        return 'Custom Protocol'

# Update protocols in the graph using the lookup
def update_protocols_in_graph_online(G):
    for u, v, d in G.edges(data=True):
        if d.get('proto') == 'Unknown Protocol':
            d['proto'] = lookup_protocol(d['port'])

# Run the update function
update_protocols_in_graph_online(G)

#step9 Drawing 
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, fcluster
from scipy.spatial.distance import pdist, squareform
import numpy as np

# Create a distance matrix based on the communication data
def create_distance_matrix(data):
    # Using pdist to create a condensed distance matrix directly
    distance_matrix = pdist(data[['pktTotalCount']], metric='euclidean')
    return distance_matrix

# Create the distance matrix
distance_matrix = create_distance_matrix(significant_communications)

# Apply hierarchical clustering on the condensed distance matrix
Z = linkage(distance_matrix, method='ward')

# Define a threshold for clustering
cluster_threshold = 0.5 * np.max(Z[:, 2])

# Get the cluster labels
cluster_labels = fcluster(Z, t=cluster_threshold, criterion='distance')

# Add cluster labels to the significant communications DataFrame

#step10
from pyvis.network import Network

# Initialize the network
net = Network(height="750px", width="100%", bgcolor="#222222", font_color="white", notebook=True, cdn_resources='in_line')

# Function to check if an IP is internet-based
def is_internet_ip(ip):
    # Assuming '192.168.x.x' and '10.x.x.x' as internal IP ranges for this example
    return not (ip.startswith("192.168.") or ip.startswith("10."))

# Add nodes and edges to the network
for _, row in significant_communications.iterrows():
    src = row['src_ip']
    dst = row['dst_ip']
    weight = row['pktTotalCount']
    service = row['service']
    protocol = row['proto']
    cluster = row['cluster']
    
    src_zone = "Internet" if is_internet_ip(src) else "Internal"
    dst_zone = "Internet" if is_internet_ip(dst) else "Internal"
    
    net.add_node(src, src, title=f"{src} ({src_zone})", group=cluster)
    net.add_node(dst, dst, title=f"{dst} ({dst_zone})", group=cluster)
    net.add_edge(src, dst, value=weight, title=f"{service}, {protocol}, {weight} pkt")

# Add filter options for clusters and physics controls
net.show_buttons(filter_=['nodes', 'edges', 'physics'])

# Generate the network visualization
html_content = net.generate_html()

# Save the network visualization using UTF-8 encoding
with open("application_topology.html", "w", encoding="utf-8") as file:
    file.write(html_content)

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, accuracy_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
# Load the dataset
file_path = r'C:\Users\Srinivasan Rangasamy\Downloads\OPCUA_dataset_public.csv'

# Select only numeric features, including 'label' and 'multi_label' columns

# Binary Classification using 'label'

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import networkx as nx

def integrated_visualization(network_graph, anomaly_nodes, anomaly_edges):
    """
    Integrate network topology with anomaly detection results.
    
    :param network_graph: NetworkX graph object representing the network topology
    :param anomaly_nodes: List of nodes identified as anomalous
    :param anomaly_edges: List of edges identified as anomalous
    """
    # Set up colors for nodes and edges
    node_colors = []
    for node in network_graph.nodes():
        if node in anomaly_nodes:
            node_colors.append('red')  # Anomalous nodes in red
        else:
            node_colors.append('lightgreen')  # Normal nodes in green
    
    edge_colors = []
    for edge in network_graph.edges():
        if edge in anomaly_edges:
            edge_colors.append('red')  # Anomalous edges in red
        else:
            edge_colors.append('black')  # Normal edges in black
    
    # Draw the network graph
    pos = nx.spring_layout(network_graph)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    nx.draw(network_graph, pos, with_labels=True, node_color=node_colors, edge_color=edge_colors, 
            node_size=500, font_size=10, font_weight='bold', width=2)
    
    plt.title('Integrated Network Topology and Anomaly Visualization')
    plt.show()

# Example usage (assuming the network_graph, anomaly_nodes, and anomaly_edges are defined)
G = nx.Graph()

# Add nodes and edges to G (this would be your network topology)
G.add_edge('A', 'B')
G.add_edge('B', 'C')
G.add_edge('C', 'D')
G.add_edge('D', 'E')

# Define anomaly nodes and edges (from your anomaly detection module)
anomaly_nodes = ['C']
anomaly_edges = [('B', 'C')]

# Call the integrated visualization function
integrated_visualization(G, anomaly_nodes, anomaly_edges)

from pyvis.network import Network
import networkx as nx

def interactive_visualization(network_graph, anomaly_nodes, anomaly_edges, output_file='network_visualization.html'):
    """
    Create an interactive network visualization with anomaly detection results.
    
    :param network_graph: NetworkX graph object representing the network topology
    :param anomaly_nodes: List of nodes identified as anomalous
    :param anomaly_edges: List of edges identified as anomalous
    :param output_file: Name of the output HTML file for the visualization
    """
    net = Network(height="750px", width="100%", bgcolor="#222222", font_color="white", directed=False)

    # Add nodes and edges to the Pyvis network
    for node in network_graph.nodes():
        color = 'red' if node in anomaly_nodes else 'lightgreen'
        net.add_node(node, label=node, color=color)

    for edge in network_graph.edges():
        color = 'red' if edge in anomaly_edges else 'black'
        net.add_edge(edge[0], edge[1], color=color)

    # Generate the interactive visualization and save it as an HTML file
    net.save_graph(output_file)
    print(f"Interactive visualization saved as {output_file}")

from pyvis.network import Network
import networkx as nx

def interactive_visualization(network_graph, anomaly_nodes, anomaly_edges, output_file='network_visualization.html'):
    net = Network(height="750px", width="100%", bgcolor="#222222", font_color="white", cdn_resources='local')

    for node in network_graph.nodes():
        color = 'red' if node in anomaly_nodes else 'lightgreen'
        net.add_node(node, label=node, color=color)

    for edge in network_graph.edges():
        color = 'red' if edge in anomaly_edges else 'black'
        net.add_edge(edge[0], edge[1], color=color)

    net.save_graph(output_file)
    print(f"Interactive visualization saved as {output_file}")
